Question: What has happened to this society ?
Answer:
Less respectful, less educated, less patient.
  
  I don’t necessarily think people have become “more sensitive” like everyone is saying. People have a platform now. The internet. Anybody can say anything they want. Before, people would just talk shit alone or to their like-minded friends and usually keep quiet to those outside of their circle. The internet has totally messed with people’s heads. Giving the ignorant the chance to spread hate and “troll” if you will. However, the internet has also connected people from around the world, formed bonds and communications that were otherwise unheard of unless you had money to travel. It has also help spread awareness for causes and helps everyone get a better understanding of what’s really happening in this world.  It’s the best and worst invention in history.
  
  In my opinion of course.

Question: Would you warn your son against marrying a woman that has 3 kids from 3 men and was divorced 3 times?
Answer:
This is a hard one. I have a son (luckily he’s a toddler for now)
  
  I also had a family member who had been married 4 times. She only had kids from 2 of the men however. BUT all of the men she was married to were abusive. She literally couldn’t catch a break. She’s since passed away about 8 years ago. So I think I’d go into that situation (if it arises) with a different perspective, I would however let my son know to be cautious.... in a lot of situations it is the woman who has the problem, but I would also encourage him to try and get her side of the story. I’d also suggest he look into her more... I mean we have the technology. I know that when I would go out with guys, I would make sure I’d look them up first (social media, etc) to try and get a sense of them, their friends, family, personality, etc. I think everyone should do that. You never know these days.

Question: What is your favorite and least favorite thing about your country?
Answer:
My favorite thing: Is the minimum wage where I live. It’s very generous.

I’m just going to assume that whoever asked this question hopefully just asked for the sake of asking and not a debate, because mama does not have the energy for that.
  
  All in all, when I see comments about “If you don’t like it then leave” is exactly why I don’t like this country more than like it. People don’t even bother being polite anymore. But they might be right, why would I want to share a country with a bunch of people who want to kick you out as soon as you let em know you have different views than they do.
  
  This country is awesome, but it has a lot of work and damage control to do stemming back a lot of years.
  
  That’s all I’m song to say about that.

Question: Advice for anyone in a abusive relationship?
Answer: Well first you need to make a plan for how you’re going to get out. Because you need to. If you’re being controlled and have limited access to money, make sure the money you do get you save it and hide it away. While you’re saving up this money, mentally plan what you’re going to take with you, I suggest a backpack worth of ONLY essentials. You can get your other stuff later with a police officer or someone you trust. Also make sure the timing is right to leave, if they lock you inside when they leave, make sure they are FULLY GONE from the house and break a window to get out. If you have zero access to money, as soon as you find a way to leave, go to a trusted person’s place... if you are isolated and don’t know anyone, the police is going to be your best bet even though I’m a little iffy with them (bad experiences). While you’re planning your escape, don’t act suspicious, that’s probably the number one way to have your plan ruined. If you have money but don’t want to go to the cops yet or at all, make sure you have enough money for a ticket of some kind if you know no one in your town/city and get the hell out of there. Basically my advice is to get out as quickly as possible.

Question: What scares you the most about our modern society?
Answer:
We are getting too comfortable with violence/death/etc.
  
  I mean I live for horror movies and am studying to become a mortician... however.
  
  The world is just becoming scarier and scarier because of people “playing god” and taking lives for the fun or fame of it.
  
  People are getting beat up for no good reason at all.
  
  In my area, we have cat killers that have not been caught, have killed/mutilated at least 13 cats and there are no leads. Information to their arrest is up to $46,000 and reportedly rising.
  
  Bad things have always happened and maybe it’s just because more atrocities are being put out there in the media... I don’t know. Either way, we as a society are getting worse... we don’t care about each other, we don’t care about keeping our planet alive which a healthy planet means healthier people and more generations getting to grow and thrive.
  
  Nothing really makes sense anymore.
  
  Sorry for the ramble! Didn’t know I felt so strongly about this 🤷🏽‍♀️

Question: What advice you would give to someone who think their self worth is linked with how many likes they get?
Answer:
This is a really tough thing to overcome, and I understand it well. The first thing I would do to approach this issue is check the notification settings in each app you post on. A lot of apps nowadays are making more specific, separate notification sliders for interaction types. If you see any notification sliders for likes, Turn Them Off. This will help keep you from coming back to check and obsess every time you might get one.
  
  Coupled with this, you have to force yourself to do the hardest (and I know, it sounds most obvious) thing: don't bother checking back on your posts. If you're doing things that make you happy, just keep looking forward onto the next thing to post! And then the next. Just don't keep turning back, because you can end up over analyzing and over criticizing yourself.
  
  Every time you get the urge to check, practice mindfulness and awareness. Tell yourself, "this is an urge coming from the self conscious part of my mind, and I won't get better if I keep entertaining it". Set your phone down and carry on with your day. You deserve better from yourself than to keep yourself spiraling down that stressful, anxious path!

Question: Paul McCartney said: "If slaughterhouses had glass walls, everyone would be a vegetarian." What do you think about it?
Answer:
I feel like it's a really powerful quote, and it shines a light on how most animal products are "gathered" (using this word loosely) in an inhumane way. It's a really important issue, and I do believe that people should have awareness of how most of these places operate. And it really is terrible, how cruel we can be.
  
  BUT... I wanted to bring this up because it feels relevant to my closing point. In high school, they had this "health ed" spokesperson come in one day during our Health period. And all this guy was there for, was to show the whole class on the projector around a slaughter house in work. That includes close up shots of animals being sIaughtered. He kept saying (to the whole class), "If you're looking away, or hiding your face, try and ask yourself why you're doing that". His whole purpose for being there was to guilt everyone out of eating meat. That entire class revolved around it that day. It was miserable.
  
  People like him sicken me. I don't at all like or "support" what goes on before I buy the animal products I consume. But I'm not about being guilt tripped, and especially not guilt tripped into changing my whole entire lifestyle. It's not right to try and do that to people. It's not educational and helpful, it's manipulative and forceful. Using guilt as a tool in order to instill a need for change into people is wrong.
  
  In short... wanting to educate others and bring awareness to others, because you care? Good. The quote you gave me is simple, but to the point. Guilt tripping others and using how awful they feel against them to coerce them into changing their lifestyle? Bad.

Question: Am I a narcissist if I heart my own questions? or answers?

Question: most welcome
Does jealousy harm relationships?
Answer:
Yes. Jealousy is an emotion that is spawned from negativity. The nąsty thing about negative emotions is that they can tend to make you spiral deeper. When you spiral, despairing over worries we've picked up on can make you act toxic. Solely because the negativity got full grip of you and is telling you you're justified.
  
  There's times where we will be jealous and it's actually justified. But it's important to sit with oneself and analyze everything rationally *ourselves*. And do it before jealousy does all the talking. If you're jealous and it's really justified, make the non-toxic decision and just end the relationship.

Question: my male friend told me that he weighs 104 pounds. he is 5' 10" should i be concerned?
Answer:
It's okay to be concerned, but to a certain extent. At the end of the day it's up to the individual what they eat and how they manage themselves. But if this is a close friend, and you know he trusts you, sit him down and ask about it. Don't be insensitive and direct by saying something like, "why are you so underweight". Try to open the conversation a little more sensitively to form a space of trust — maybe ask, "Are you okay". If he asks why you're asking, say something like, "I have been concerned about your wellbeing since you talked about your weight".
  
  It's important to keep in mind that people can be underweight for a plethora of reasons — from eating disorders to conditions that cause weight loss. Since you don't seem to know the cause, it's important to approach this conversation by being sensitive and open ended. Don't throw around things like, "you need to eat more" or "you're too skinny" because frankly things like that are ıgnorant and not needed — they don't help. And don't pry if it seems like he's uncomfortable to talk about it. Leave the conversation open on your end, but let his responses / reactions be signs of when it's time to back off. Just let him know he has  a place to talk about it without judgement.

Question: Ever wonder how the world would end?
Answer:
The end of the world is something that I've always wondered about. And I pondered upon it a whole lot more during 2020.
  
  I don't even necessarily mean in a negative, doomy gloomy way. Sure there were a lot of bad days that caused those thoughts to be incredibly negative. But most of the time, I actually wonder about it because of curiosity about our own mortalıty. I'm talking about how we start a story on this planet that we will never truly Finish.
  
  Sure, our own individual stories will end. But the vastness of the universe — and heII even just planet Earth alone — makes me feel like our individual stories are just mere chapters in the whole story of life. It makes me feel like myself and all around me, is small. A lot of those feelings all tie back to the fact that we currently living beings will likely not see the end of Everything.
  
  To be honest, I don't think I'm content with that. Even if it's grim, I am always wanting to know. It would just be a funky form of closure for me to know what's going to happen to the planet I lived on, loved, and explored.

Question: If you dislike someone, how can they tell?
Answer:
In person, I think a lot of the signs come from body language and facial expressions. Maybe even the person's tone when they speak to you. If these kind of negative signs keep showing up specifically when you interact with a person, it could be an indication that they dislike you.
  
  But then again, it's hard to settle on that answer because a lot of problems are started by getting the wrong idea. Making the wrong assumptions on accident, due to being anxious. I remember learning from this educational video that anxiety can actually mess with that part of the brain that reads and processes body signals. Your anxiety can make you see things much worse than they actually are, like facial expressions and body language.
  
  All of the fretting can do much more harm than good. So in conclusion, the best way to tell if someone dislikes you is to just ask outright. It's not a fun thing to do, and it's pretty embarrassing because it puts you on the spot. But hey, you'll finally get an answer straight from the source of your worry. And that's worth the trouble I think, because prolonging worry is just too draining.

Question: is it easier to fall in love or fall out of love?

Question: Do you run from neighborhood animals like skunks, opossums, raccoons & deer?
Answer:
No, no! Never. I'll keep a distance from skunks, but the rest? I like to stick around, admire, and if I'm lucky enough to I'll feed them! Actually, since we're talking about wild animals..
  
  There's a raccoon that has taken to coming by sometimes, since a few months ago, because of the food we leave in Salem's dish. Salem is the stray cat that we've been taking care of since last year.
  
  Anyways, sometimes he leaves food behind in his bowl. And not a lot of people know this, but domesticated raccoons can actually get a balanced diet from cat food. They quite like it! So when Salem wasn't there, guess who was? A raccoon! We actually caught the raccoon sleeping in Salem's bed once. And more than a couple times did we find him snooping on the porch to see if Salem had leftovers.
  
  The last time we found him on the porch, he was "hissing" at us to leave him alone. Then I extended my hand down with some cat food and dropped it. And the raccoon looked at me with this weird newfound understanding, before bowing his head and patting the floor of the porch to find pieces of cat food to eat.
  
  Anyways, I would seldom ever run from animals. They are all trying to get by, just as much as we are. This is a really dangerous neighborhood, so I can only imagine how hard it is for them to survive when they're living outside in all of it. If I can extend a hand and a little bit of food here and there to help them, I will. I mean, I've been shamelessly late for work before, just because I was feeding squirrels. It's just the kind of person I am.

Question: Is it best to defend people, or should they do it, themselves? Is self-defense always a learned behavior?
Answer:
Self-defense is, in most people, a learned behavior. Not everyone is able to utilize their feelings (be it fear, anxiety, stress, etc) to channel their defenses. For those, it can take a lot of guidance and practice to be able to hone their ability to defend themselves.
  
  So that being said, it's important that those of us who *do* know how to defend ourselves lend a hand to those who do not. All it can take is one helpful hand to guide someone. And that helpful hand might just save a life, for one reason or the other. No one should try and "be a hero" — but serving acts of kindness to those in need shouldn't be looked down upon.

Question: Who is your favorite villain from a movie, show etc.? What makes you love to hate them? 😈
Answer:
I took a lot of interest in Oswald  Cobblepot (The Penguin) — specifically from Gotham. I never really had much knowledge of the Batman universe outside of a couple of things I'd seen, so Gotham was my biggest dive into it. A lot of the villains from the Batman universe were present, so needless to say it was my first introduction to a lot of these characters. But I really do think watching the parts with The Penguin were my favorite.
  
  For some reason, the build of his character throughout the seasons was really fascinating to see unfold. He starts off as a nobody who would eventually start conniving and manipulating his way to the top, being kicked down and climbing on back over and over.  He's a sneaky bąstard, and the sneaky bąstard characters are so interesting because they're psychologically complex. The whole journey that was showed with this character made me keep wondering "what's next". Genuinely, I felt that he was written out and acted out excellently.

It's hard to determine how to eliminate a stressful situation. Most of the time, the best one can do is try to eliminate the stress that's being felt.

  If all else fails, the only other option is to find ways to cope.

Question: What would be good advice for a guy on getting to know a girl without coming off weird? We work together, but I don’t know how to approach her :/
Answer:
I wouldn't rush into confessing / asking her out or anything. Spend some time striking up casual conversations! It's a good idea to start talking about common things, like work and such. If the opportunity is present over time, talk about stuff outside of work.
  
  To ease into that, start sprinkling in some stuff about yourself during conversation. Sometimes people feel more comfortable opening up about their personal lives if the other person in the conversation does it first. Some people prefer to keep their personal lives outside of work, however. So if you get signs that she's uncomfortable breaking past that coworker commonplace talk, it's best to pull back and assess the situation. Chances are if she's not interested in talking about aspects of her life outside of work to a coworker, she wouldn't be interested in dating a coworker.
  
  Take your time, be patient, allow room for casual conversations first! And good luck.

Question: what are your thoughts on both PS5 and Xbox Series X being $500? Too expensive? Just right?

  A good gaming PC has quite the expense to swallow, sure. But I'd much rather set myself up on a payment plan for a beefy upgradable pre-build (or heII just the parts for building my own). It's better than tossing $500 out the window on something that will continually lose usability once the next one comes out.
  
  A good gaming PC (and one with upgradable parts) promises support for games of the past, present, and future. I'll take that over a console any day. It's just so much more worth it!

Question: Do you support "free relationship"? Meaning dating multiple people at once and not being limited to one person?
Answer:
That's actually called "poIyamory" — and yes, I support it! There's absolutely nothing wrong with healthy poIyamorous relationships. And when I say healthy, I mean two key important things:
  
  * {Everyone is in the know} — Complete transparency. Being involved with people behind the backs of everyone you're seeing is NOT poIyamory; it is cheating. It's important that everyone you're seeing knows up-front what your intentions are.
  
  * {Everyone agrees and consents} — Everyone involved knows that you are poIyamorous, and that you are seeing other people, AND everyone is fully okay with that.  Be communicative and honest.
  
  As an example, I am poIyamorous actually. And my partner is monogamous. We have talked about my want to explore other relationships, and together we have agreed on it! We have our own specific terms of Do's and Don'ts that work best for the well-being of our relationship. And it's about as easy-peasy as that!
  
  Everyone is different though. If you yourself are in a relationship with someone who is monogamous and doesn't want a poIyamorous partner.. it's for the better to end that relationship. Limiting yourself will only make you unhappy, which makes your partner unhappy. And going behind your partner's back despite them not wanting the relationship to be that way is just as bad, if not worse.
  
  Anyways. Yes, I support poIyamory. Because just like with monogamous relationships, they can be healthy OR unhealthy. It all depends on compatability and communication!

Question: Is eBay trustworthy for buying Computers, Gaming consoles, or phone from a 100% reliable vendor?
Answer:
No, no, no and a thousand times NO!!! Even if there's pics and vids with it powered on, there could be a plethora of problems you (as the buyer) cannot see.
  
  If you're looking to buy a computer, it could have a virus. If you're looking to buy a console, it could be quick to overheating or it won't read disks properly. Oh and don't get me started on all of the issues a phone could potentially have, besides it being someone's phone that the seller stole and factory reset.
  
  I'm really just putting out some issues that tech stuff could have when resold online. Remember: if something looks too good to be true, it probably is. Ebay is strictly person to person, and the person selling stuff to you might not be 100% reliable and honest. It's important to keep your guard up on sites like  eBay. ESPECIALLY since support rarely intervenes on purchases once said and done.
  
  Trust your gut. Be critical. Be careful.

Question: Are you someone who replies to messages (such as texts) immediately, or do you wait? Do you get impatient if others reply to you late?
Answer:
For your first question, it depends on a few factors. Like if a person JUST sent the message. If that's the case, I'll wait a couple of minutes to try and leave "breathing room" between messages. Some other factors are where I am, what I'm doing, and how busy I am. But generally, if I see a message notification I try to be on it within ten minutes!
  
  As for your second question, I don't feel like it's fair to be impatient with people who aren't replying "fast enough" to your liking. It's selfish, and shows a lack of care (and general understanding) for the other person's situation. It's unrealistic to expect someone's continuous availability. And besides, we aren't meant to be clinging to our phones waiting for the next reply! Text is for the convenience of speaking to a person as soon as possible while you're doing things in your own world. It shouldn't be held to the same expectations that face to face conversation and phone calls have.

Question: Today is international day of persons with disabilities. What's something you feel people should know about either disabilities in general, people with disabilities or a specific disability?
Answer:
There's so many things that able bodied people need to learn about physical disabilities, and so many things that neurotypical people need to learn about mental disabilities. Ableism for both physical and mental disabilities is alive and rampant, and the lack of proper education and attention on the topic doesn't help. But here's some helpful things I think everyone should keep in mind / think about / exercise:
  
  .‎˖٭ ✩ Disabled persons do not want you to treat them differently for their disability. They want to be treated like everyone else: with human decency and respect. (Some of my points ahead will show what I mean)
  

  .‎˖٭ ✩ Maintain eye contact when you talk. People with physical disabilities will feel uncomfortable and self conscious if you gawk at the equipment that assists them. Avoid putting visual attention on their equipment unless they ask.
  
  .‎˖٭ ✩ Do not be patronizing with your interactions. Do not do "baby talk" or use pet names. This kind of treatment is humiliating, even if you mean well.
  
  .‎˖٭ ✩ Avoid showing pity / treating disabled people as if they are victims. Again even if you mean well, it is degrading.
  
  .‎˖٭ ✩ Always be mindful of your language when you speak about disabilities, and persons with a lack thereof. Examples: Do not call a person a "cripple" or call them "deformed" — terms like this are offensive and make disabled people feel abnormal. Do not refer to non disabled people as "normal" or "healthy" — it implies something is "wrong" with disabled persons. Using "non disabled" or "able-bodied" is fine.
  
  .‎˖٭ ✩ NEVER physically assist unless you are asked to, most especially with their assisting equipment and their bodies. Do not (without permission): push a person's wheelchair, physically lift them, or touch their equipment.
  
  .‎˖٭ ✩ Do NOT mess with service dogs. They are on duty, meaning that distractions away from their duties assisting a person around is dangerous to their handler.

Question: Do you even wear a mask or are you like 'PFFFTTT' ??

Question: hi beautiful
what do you like to do for fun
Answer:
Tons of things! I'll list off some of my all time favorite things to do. These are some of my favorite activities:
  
  * playing games - I primarily play on my PC, but I also have my 3DS. Also, I use my phone and computer as emulators for a great number of systems!
  
  * reading - I mostly read Webtoon comics and manga. But I would love recommendations for full books, as I want to do much more reading in the near future.
  
  * drawing - It's not something I do often anymore because of a lack of inspiration. But I used to draw all of the time, and still quite enjoy it! My primary method for creating art was pixel art, because I find it to be really charming.
  
  * cooking - Mostly experimentally!! I have only a few recipes down pat that I know how to make well. Like tacos, for instance.
  
  * creating small ascii - I like to make kaomoji (like unicode faces, such as ( ٥˶⩌ ⩊⩌)୨՞՞ which I made recently), animals, and sometimes small bio / drop down layouts for Vent.
  
  * biking - This is one I haven't done in a while, because the last time I did someone came into the yard and stole it. I've been hesitant to take it back out since we took it back!! Plus crime rates are really high here this year, But I really have been itching to go on a bike ride.
  
  * nature walking - Almost nothing brings on more peace and calm than a good walk through a thicket of woods! But it's also fun to me, because I get to see new plants to take pictures of. And if I'm lucky, maybe even some wildlife.
  
  * taking pictures - I like to take pictures of plants and animals! Like if I'm taking a hike and I see a neat looking flower, I'll usually take the time to snap a good shot of it.
  
  * feeding local wildlife - Strays, raccoons, squirrels.. I love taking care of them!
  
  * singing - MOSTLY by myself. I've only sung to and around a couple of people. But I do think it's fun!
  
  * discovering new music - Sometimes I'll do a deep dive through Spotify and Bandcamp to discover new music that might suit my tastes.

Question: how true are you with all your promises?

  An example of this is, "I promise I'll always be here for you". This is a promise that I make to people I love and care about, with the best intentions. An unforeseeable occurrence that would waive this promise, is if that person were being crappy and I had to cut them off.
  
  Barring anything bad happening that would stop me from keeping a promise.. I am a person of my word.

Question: Opinion on indigenous people hunting/killing animals
Answer:
Indigenous peoples depend on the environment / land in which they live for resources. They build their communities within that land, grow their roots there, and they have been doing that for thousands of years before we even came close to it. So with that being said, it's important that (we) non indigenous individuals respect their heritage. We need to understand that those lands are theirs to have rational jurisdictions over. And them being allowed to reasonably use the resources around them to survive is absolutely rational.
  
  Also, what actually we need to worry about is commercial hunters and poachers. These are the people who use nature selfishly and wastefully, cause species extinction, and do harm to the environment. Not people who have been hunting as a means to survival naturally for thousands of years.

Question: Have you ever had a toxic relationship (be it romantic, familial, or a friendship) and how did you deal with it? Did you cut ties or did you find a way to mend the relationship?
Answer:
I actually just recently ended a relationship that was becoming rapidly toxic. It ended with me cutting ties completely, because the way I was being treated was poor. All of it was putting my mental health through the wringer, so when it was getting to be too painful and no hope was left— *I* left. And yeah, I did put in the effort and time to try and "fix" it. But I want to REALLY emphasize this:
  
  You Can't Fix Everything— and that is Okay. It's not your responsibility to try and "fix" someone's toxic behaviors. This kind of thing goes beyond just wasting time. Doing this always ends up with you repeatedly subjecting yourself to pain. All at the sake of trying to fix someone else's emotional misgivings. The damage all of that can do to you is significant! At the end of the day, sometimes you have to evaluate what it's really worth to try. And to also genuinely evaluate how much hurt you're getting into by trying.
  
  REMEMBER: it's up to the individual to work on themselves and their growth. That's not really something you can just give to a person.

Question: When does loyalty become too much?
Answer:
Loyalty becomes too much when it smothers your light.
  
  Loyalty to someone / something is how we communicate interest, love, passion, and devotion. How could any of that be bad, right? Well, when that loyalty to a person / thing you like begins to consume every part of your life.. are you really living? Do you have individuality, or is your free will motivated by who / what you're loyal to?
  
  Loyalty is a good thing. But when it creeps into every unrelated turn in our life, it consumes the individual. It's important for oneself to have the time and allowance to pursue personal interests, friendships, goals, aspirations, and dreams. To pursue *INDIVIDUALITY*.
  
  You can be a loyal person and still have individuality. You can still be loyal to what you love and still pursue different branches of your life around that. But if your reason for loyalty feels threatened by your sense of individuality.. it's time to change things up. Before it consumes the rest of who you are.

Question: If you could live forever, would you want to?
Answer: For a very long time, because of depression, my answer to this was no. Because who would want an eternity of pain, right? But as I grew and developed to where I am now, I am beyond that. I see the world in a much brighter life in the prospect of living forever. Living forever sounds perfect, actually. I mean imagine actually having ALL of time in the world. My life would be timeless, so I would feel less pressure to do everything I want to do. I can space things out and find more time to relax! Also in terms of time, there's the fact that I'll be able to observe generation after generation to come. See the development of society, and technology, and architecture.. just SO MANY THINGS! Also, I'll be able to witness the end of the world. Which I know is grim, but.. I started this story and I want to see how it finishes.

Question: Do you believe in love at first sight? Why or why not?

You don't know the person besides their exterior, or their appearance. You don't know their story, personality, hardships, quips and quirks; n o t h i n g. Question: what's your advice to people who likes to have/achieve a healthy long hair?
Answer:
I can offer a few really helpful tips I've learned over the years for healthy hair. I'm not sure about achieving long hair growth other than patience though!! Anyways, here's what I do know in terms of having healthy hair:
  
  * NEVER was your hair with water that's too warm. Hot water can cause damage to the fibers of our hair, and it's the most common cause of hair breakage. Try using lukewarm / cool water.
  
  * Ensure you're using shampoo and conditioner, not 2-in-1! Picking a shampoo and conditioner set that works with our hair type is essential for increasing the health of your hair. Using shortcut products like 2-in-1 doesnt nourish and protect our strands, nor does it get it properly cleaned.
  
  * Don't wash your hair nightly! Make sure to have "skip nights" — nights where you won't wash your hair at all. I usually wash one day, then skip the next, and wash the day after. Following that pattern doesn't stress out our strands! Excessive washing can cause breakage.

Question: Are you a class reductionist?
Answer:
This is actually my first time hearing the term! But upon looking into it, I don't at all resonate with it.
  
  "The idea in some leftist circles that all oppression based on gender, sex, race, etc. is just a byproduct of class struggle, and that once class disparity is solved, all those issues will vanish"
  
  While class differences do impact all of us, there's plenty of other forms of oppression that need individually tackled. Those forms of oppression do not directly correlate with class separation; instead they have to do with personal prejudice and hate for those who are different from ourselves. It's asinine to even come close to implying that these deep rooted social issues will vanish once we resolve class differences.
  
  Anyways I'm just providing my opinion based on what I've read on the term. And based upon what I've gathered, I do not relate to it.

  Photography is a beautiful thing. The technology is in our hands, and I think it's kinda beautiful that we can share little stories about our lives, one image at a time. Question: Do you agree with the statement, "Never meet your heroes"? Why or why not?
Answer:
OH YES, ABSOLUTELY. There's a couple of things that come to mind when I hear of that statement:
  
  1) It's important to be mindful with *who* and *how* we admire others. Looking up to someone is one thing, but it's dangerous to idolize someone. Especially a celebrity; someone who puts on a face to the world. They're someone you truly know nothing about!
  
  2) Many people idolize celebrities, and for some people that devotion ends up with them being "lucky" enough to finally meet their idol! A "once in a lifetime" opportunity.. I have heard so many stories of this going wrong and it absolutely crushing people.
  
  Usually in these stories I've heard, people eagerly go to get an autograph from their idol, only for them to be met with unexpected "out of character" abrasive attitude and rude behavior. And what crushes those people is forever being left with wondering: "Why? Why did my idol act that way to me? Was it me? Were they having a bad day? Is this really who they are?" — they're left to despair over that for the rest of their lives. Because as I said, meeting your idol is a "once in a lifetime" opportunity. If it goes wrong, it can be hope crushing. Permanently.

Question: Are funny people necessarily smart?

Question: Will you stay in a toxic relationship just because you get used to it?
Answer:
Nope! This kind of piggy-backs off of my previous answer buuut the point is just the same: It would be a fat waste of my valuable time. I wouldn't ever want to stay with someone who I believe would be genuinely toxic for me. If a person can't treat other people right, then they shouldn't be getting into relationships. And they certainly don't deserve to be in one with me.
  
  But this should go without saying (generally speaking) : It can be hard for people in abusive relationships to see just how bad the abuse really is. Because like you said, it's wholly possible to get used to it. It's wholly possible to be convinced that THATS what you have, and that's what you'll always have. It's wholly possible to be manipulated into believing so many good things surrounding an abuser because these toxic monsters are so good at what they do: being bad.
  
  So please don't use my answer as a "gotcha" for anyone who is in an abusive relationship, or to ridicule anyone who is stuck in one. That would be absolutely unfair and downright sickening. People who are enduring toxicity from a partner or abuse need support, patience, and guidance. Not ridicule. If you know a loved one who is going through this, be supportive. Be kind. Be the light they need to be able to see in the world.

Question: Will you ever try to be in a relationship out of convenience?

Question: does it really got better, or do we just get used to it?
Answer:
I truthfully believe that the going gets easier over time! Whether or not it's part of us "getting used to it" is totally situational, but I for the most part hold the belief that things just get better. There is so much good in the world to experience to keep stuck in the mindset that things won't ever change!
  
  I used to struggle a lot with shifting this mentality around, but it was over the passage of time that I was able to. I don't think it was from getting used to my problems, though. I think that more or less, I got into the "it gets better" mindset by surviving through all of my struggles. Getting through those troubles made me stronger, more aware, and more level headed so that I might cope. And now that I'm better at coping, I have the ability to strive for better. It just takes time.

Question: why do good people still struggle and experience bad stuff?
Answer:
An important part of coping in hard times is first understanding this: pain and suffering do not correlate to who we are as people. A lot of people find themselves in such deep hurt that they spiral down a path of taking it out on themselves. Holding the belief that one simply "must have earned it" to be going through hard times is an example of this.
  
  I promise, no matter how much agony you're shouldering, it's not a punishment. It's not happening because you did something wrong. In truth, bad things happen to everyone, good or bad. It's important to understand that it's all a part of life. Life is full of ups and downs, and unfortunately we all sometimes go through those downs! Some of us go through it harder than others, but all the same it's not a direct stab at us from the universe when it happens.
  
  Unfortunately there's no real "how" or "why" answer to satisfy this question. What matters is that we don't take it out on ourselves or others, and that we do our best to keep moving forward. I hope you find healing soon.

Question: What do you do when someone is being irritating?

Have never had a problem with that.
  
  If, however, it's a total stranger being irritating.. they are usually doing it on purpose. I'm not afraid of being a little more blunt. Not harsh, not brutal: just *blunt*. Forward. These people are usually in surprise that someone as soft in appearance as me can be that way so that usually ends it. If by chance they continue, I hope they enjoy being ignored. They're not worth the time or energy of even being recognized beyond that point.

Question: Do you believe in destiny/karma? Do you think people get what they deserve, or is the world more unfair?
Answer:
It's hard to 100% believe in forces that directly alter our realities; I continously have a back and forth about this within myself. I feel.. maybe that I don't believe in destiny and karma in their root definitions.
  
  Like, karma is supposed to be something good or bad happening as a *direct result* of a prior action, right? And I mean not something as simple as someone committing crimes and getting the "karma" of being arrested. I mean that's more predictable. I'm talking more or less two completely unrelated scenarios happening.
  
  For example, someone breaks a heart. They get their heart broken in the future. Can we really believe that that's the universe's punishment? It sounds all too.. coincidental. I think the concept of karma, or people "getting what they've earned" is a comforting one. But it's hard to fully, 100% believe in it all.

Question: if cinderella's shoes fit perfectly then how did it slip off?
Answer:
Women's shoes (especially fancy / "dress" shoes) are often created with the most impractical design. They're not made to accommodate the wearer for much activity other that swift, smooth, elegant footsteps. Most particularly, the type of shoes Cinderella was wearing.
  
  They're referred to as "slippers" because that's what they do: slip. They aren't made with an ankle or over-the-foot strap, solely for the convenience of being able to "slip" the shoes on and off. That being said, it'd be easy to lose one in fast paced activity, such as when she was running. Sucker just *pop*! Slipped right off. There's nothing to keep it in place!

Question: Should we forgive our enemies? Why/why not?
Answer: No, I don't think we should ever have to forgive someone who hurt us. The concept that we absolutely *have to* forgive and forget "in order to heal" is incredibly toxic. Question: do gadgets control us or do we control gadgets?
Answer:
We control gadgets. Inanimate objects are physically incapable of being in control of us. The only thing that manipulates what we do and how long we do something is attachment and addiction. The device itself isn't controlling us. It isn't forcing us to use it. It isn't holding us hostage. When someone gets really into using their tech, it's either because they're attached to their networks or they thrive from whatever they get out of it. When something gives you a grand amount of satisfaction, often like nothing else could, it's hard to put down. That's where the loss of control comes in: solely within the individual.
  
  SO basically, this notion that our devices control us absolves responsibility of the individual. It instead puts blame on the device for how much we use it. It's important to move the focal point to Ourselves. And if necessary, make adjustments on just how reliant we are on these devices.

Question: Do you think it's okay to pay for cleaning your own home?
Answer:
From a moralistic standpoint, I don't really agree with it. I feel like it absolves the home owner of personal responsibility from their own messes. As someone who has worked in cleaning, I have seen this firsthand.
  
  Essentially, once a person knows they have someone to come in and magically poof away the mess, they feel careless and free to be piggish. Messes are a problem of the past to these people. They act more careless with their very own spaces because they know they no longer have to. They're paying someone else to care, after all. Basically that's the kind of attitude these people who pay for personal cleaning services seem to carry.
  
  I just feel like it's important for a person to be responsible for what they've done. Like, why make a mess for someone else to fix? So long as you're physically able, I think you (not personal, I mean general "you") should clean your own messes. It keeps you active, and in healthy mindsets. It keeps you from becoming a slob that is reliant on helping hands to do work for you.

Question: Do you think you get more mature by getting older?
Answer:
Yes, and no. Or, rather.. yes and THEN for most people there's a stopping point in that maturing. Allow me to explain.
  
  The more we age, the more we are able to experience! Relationships, exploration, individuality, independence, you name it. We gain a lot of knew knowledge with new experiences. And most life changing experiences happen as we age through adulthood. But for a lot of people there's a stunt in their mental growth and maturity when they reach a certain point. It can be a lack of willingness to do new things, or a level of comfort with where a person is at. Or, a complete disinterest in working on things that make us better.
  
  UGH I could have put this more simply I think, and when I re-read your question I keep thinking I'm going about this the wrong way. My bad! I think what I'm trying to say is: yes, you do mature a lot more as you age. But there's a lot of people who aren't willing to be mature about certain things about themselves in order to *keep* maturing.

Question: does growing up change your body or also your soul?
Answer: Growth isn't ever just a physical thing! Everything invested in you changes; mind, body, and spirit. As we age, we all experience a plethora of different things that tailor us into who we become. Gaining friends, making enemies, loving, losing: these are some of the biggest things that change what's on the inside as we grow. And as long as a person keeps on exploring new things, and new possibilities, I truly believe there's no stop in growth. Some people out of ignorance *choose* not to search for internal growth, however, and that's the unfortunate disconnect. But that's them. For me, however, I'll always consider myself a work in progress. Up until my very death.

Question: I act differently depending on the people around me. Am I fake?

And keeping people you like around pleases you.
  
  Overall, it would be one thing if you were doing it to be spiteful to these "different people" behind their backs and act like they're strangers when you're with others. However if you're doing it as a natural response, or to keep others happy, I don't necessarily think that's "fake". You're taking in the information around you and adapting based on what you come up with in that case.

Question: What is  the purpose of love???
Answer:
Love has many purposes! First it's important that we separate the words "love" and "romance" if we are going to grasp any base understanding, however. Because while romance can be motivated by love, the two aren't the same! Love by itself is to feel intense care for something or someone.
  
  I feel like the purpose of love itself is  to be an influence on one's whole life. Love connects us to the places we live, the locations we favor, the people we make our friends, those we choose to be partnered with, etc. Most of the choices that we make revolve around it. Love is a feeling that helps us find out what we want to surround ourselves with, and it helps us know what makes us ultimately happy.
  
  Do I feel like love of any kind should be the only guiding compass in our subset of emotions? No. But I do feel like it plays one of the most significant roles in choice making and path taking. We are a curious species, brought into this world to give and receive over and over again until we are Done. With love influencing so much, it's one of the key elements that make that cycle continue.

Question: How’d you get your profile name to have the word “cute” above angel like that? Pretty neat! ☺️
Answer:
I used one of my favorite text generating websites!
  

   https://yaytext.com/mini-me/
  

  The one I used is called "mini stacked", and you have to put in what you want like this:
  
  top small text
  
  bottom normal text
  
  And the generator will turn the text on top into tiny text! But do be aware: not every letter of the alphabet stacks neatly above the regular sized text! Also, your top word should probably be smaller than or the same length as your bottom word to avoid more character dipping.

Question: What’s the nicest thing a complete stranger has done for you? 💙
Answer:
What comes to mind is the homeless woman who helped me find my way, my first time traveling by myself. I was going to Illinois to visit with my partner for a little while, and I was going by megabus. We were just dropped off on (what seemed to be) just some random road. And it was pouring rain. Everyone else seemed to know where they were going but I was lost. I was in a massive city with a bunch of luggage, all by myself.
  
  Eventually a woman comes up and asks for some money. She said she's trying to make her way to a woman's shelter to escape from an abusive situation. I gave her some money. I think she could tell I was new around because I looked a whole mess. She offered her spare jacket to me, and told me the ways I need to go to get to my destination. She even stopped our Uber later on when she saw me to make sure that I was safe and with someone I wanted to be with. I said yes, and we parted ways.

Question: So I’m pregnant and I really have been thinking about just disappearing out of the city away from everyone. Would I be wrong to ghost my child’s father to?
Answer: If being pregnant is sincerely making you feel like leaving everything behind and running away from the life you currently have (dangerous, do not do this), I think you should sit and think about why that is. And perhaps consider the possibility that maybe having a child isn't right for you. If it isn't too late in your pregnancy, I would have an abortion. If you carry this child and go off to live a life of uncertainty by yourself, you'll be giving your child a hard life. That's not a kind of situation to bring a new life into. It's okay to be scared and not be ready to be a parent. It's normal. But there are options out there for you so that you don't have to be a parent if you're not ready. Stay safe.
